---
/** Hub: W-2G withholding reconciliation. Worked example by w2gReconcile(). */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import W2GCalculator from '../../components/calculators/W2GCalculator.tsx';
import { w2gReconcile } from '../../lib/gambling';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const ex = w2gReconcile(10000, 60000, 0, 'single', 0);
---

<Base
  title="W-2G calculator 2026 — gambling withholding vs tax"
  description="Your W-2G withholds a flat 24% on gambling winnings — but that's a prepayment, not your final tax. See whether you'll get a refund or owe more at filing."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>W-2G calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">The 24% the casino withheld is a guess, not your tax. It's usually wrong in one direction or the other.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    When a gambling win is large enough, the payer issues a W-2G and withholds a
    flat 24% for federal tax. But 24% is rarely your actual rate — in a lower
    bracket it over-withholds and you get money back; in a higher bracket it
    under-withholds and you owe more. This reconciles the withholding against the
    real tax the winnings cause.
  </p>

  <W2GCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — a {formatMoney(10000)} W-2G</h2>
  <p>
    A filer with {formatMoney(60000)} of other income hits a {formatMoney(10000)}
    jackpot reported on a W-2G:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Figure</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>24% federal withheld</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.federalWithheld)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Actual federal tax the winnings cause</td><td>{formatMoney(ex.actualFederalTax)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>{ex.difference >= 0 ? 'Refunded at filing' : 'Still owed at filing'}</td><td>{formatMoney(Math.abs(ex.difference))}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    The casino withheld {formatMoney(ex.federalWithheld)}, but at this filer's 22%
    bracket the winnings only cost {formatMoney(ex.actualFederalTax)} in federal tax —
    so {formatMoney(Math.abs(ex.difference))} comes back as a refund. A high earner
    in the 37% bracket would see the opposite: the 24% under-withholds and they owe
    the difference plus state tax.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>When does a casino issue a W-2G?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      At set thresholds by game: generally $1,200+ on slots or bingo, $1,500+ on
      keno, $5,000+ in a poker tournament, and $600+ at 300-to-1 odds elsewhere.
      Above the reporting level the payer often withholds 24%. Below it, no form is
      issued — but the winnings are still fully taxable.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is the 24% my final tax?</h3>
    <p>
      No — it is a prepayment credited on your return, like paycheck withholding. Your
      actual rate depends on your total income. You reconcile at filing: refund if
      over-withheld, balance due if under. State tax is separate and usually not
      withheld at all.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What if I have no W-2G?</h3>
    <p>
      You still owe tax. The W-2G is a reporting form, not the trigger for the tax —
      all gambling winnings are taxable whether or not one is issued, and nothing was
      withheld on them, so set money aside. The
      <a href="/gambling-tax-calculator/">gambling tax calculator</a> handles the full picture.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Can I offset it with losses?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      Only by itemizing, and for 2026 only 90% of losses are deductible, capped at
      winnings. If you take the standard deduction, losses do nothing and the 24%
      withheld may still fall short of your real tax. Keep a gambling diary either way.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/gambling-tax-calculator/">Gambling tax calculator</a> — the full picture</li>
    <li><a href="/lottery-tax-calculator/">Lottery tax calculator</a> — lump sum vs annuity</li>
    <li><a href="/quarterly-tax-calculator/">Quarterly tax calculator</a> — setting aside for a win</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Estimate for the 2026 tax year. The W-2G withholding is a prepayment; state tax
    is extra. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
